Drivers of data structure

Jeff Powell

23 September 2019

Up to this point, we have used ordination to look for structure in multivariate data. Once that structure is observed, you may have ideas about what factors are driving that structure and would like to test the hypotheses that these factors are actually important. To do this is to apply a constraint to the data, partitioning variation in the data to specific factors, or linear combinations of these specific factors (as above), and then comparing this partitioned variation to any remaining variation in the data.

Here we use the phyloseq object called phy that we generated during the first chapter and modified in the second chapter. This object has been manipulated to include only OTUs that have been classified as fungi and successfully classified at the phylum level. OTU data were hellinger-transformed and excluded five samples that had low read counts.

‘Experimental’ frameworks: working with factors

Cluster analysis

We often collect multivariate data in the context of experimental studies or in the context of observed categorical explanatory variables that are of interest. We could perform ANOVA for each variable individually, but this amplifies the potential for Type I error and does not account for potential collinearity among response variables. In addition, we may not be interested in particular response variables, but in how multiple variables are responding as a whole.

We have already seen strong separation in our data by sample type and weak separation by fertilizer treatment through ordination. We can also visualise this by plotting hierarchical clusters. We will use the complete-linkage algorithm, which is the default and aims to maximise the distances among clusters, but other algorithms are available and may be more appropriate.

# set plot margins
par(mar=c(5,4,2,2))

# plot hclust result, using distance matrix and input
plot(hclust(dist(otu_table(phy), method='euclidean')))

The label on the tips represent the rownames in the OTU matrix but are not very informative on their own. Here it is useful to provide a more informative vector with which to label the tips.

# set plot margins
par(mar=c(5,4,2,2))

# manipulate labels to include in the plot
# first select columns to use
temp <- select(sample_data(phy), Treatment, SampleType)
# then change labels of legend to something shorter
levels(temp$Treatment) <- c('-', 'N', 'P', 'NP')
levels(temp$SampleType) <- c('Root', 'Soil')
# then combine the two factors into a single vector
temp$trt <- with(temp, interaction(SampleType, Treatment, sep=' '))

# plot output of hierarchical clustering using custom labels
plot(hclust(dist(otu_table(phy), method='euclidean')), 
     labels=temp$trt)

# tidy workspace
rm(temp)

Statistical testing

We need a statistical tool to test the hypothesis that fungal communities within each group are more similar to each other than to those under other groups.

Analysis of similarities (ANOSIM) is one approach to test this hypothesis, using the anosim function in the vegan package. This is a nonparametric test; distances are transformed into ranks and the mean of the ranks for distances classified as within the groups is compared to that for the between-group distance ranks. However, there are concerns about how ANOSIM results should be interpreted (also mentioned on the help page for the function) and PerMANOVA (Permutational ANOVA) is usually preferred.

PerMANOVA is potentially more powerful than ANOSIM because the distances are preserved and not rank-transformed; the approach partitions variance among and within groups through calculations of sums of squared distances and calculates pseudo \(F\)-statistics. In addition, it is possible to estimate the effects associated with multiple factors and their interactions. The function to perform PerMANOVA is adonis within vegan and the result is interpreted in the same way as an ANOVA table.

# extract sample data and change to data.frame class
# note that 'as.data.frame' leaves as 'sample_data' object, 
# which does not work with adonis
dat <- data.frame(sample_data(phy))

# perform PerMANOVA using Euclidean distances (for RDA)
adonis(dist(otu_table(phy), method='euclidean') ~ SampleType * Treatment, 
       data=dat)

Because we used blocking in our experimental design, we should include BlockID as the strata argument to constrain permutations to within this group. Note that we cannot do this for PlotID to account for multiple sample types since this would not allow for correct reshuffling of Treatment labels.

adonis(dist(otu_table(phy), method='euclidean') ~ SampleType * Treatment, 
       data=dat, strata=dat$BlockID)

There appears to be a weak effect of Treatment but we can’t tell how the levels differ from each other using this result. Functions in the pairwiseAdonis library produce pairwise comparisons – pairwise.adonis is appropriate when making comparisons within a single factor. Here we use pairwise.adonis2 to constrain permutations to within levels of SampleType.

# load library
library(pairwiseAdonis)

# test comparisons
pairwise.adonis2(dist(otu_table(phy), method='euclidean') ~ Treatment, 
       data=dat, strata='SampleType')

From this it looks like there are differences when the levels differ in whether phosphorus was added. Alternatively, in this case, we could separate the effects of N and P, as follows:

# split 'Treatment' into separate variables for 'N' and 'P'
dat$N <- factor(with(dat, ifelse(Treatment %in% c('N', 'NP'), 'yesN', 'noN')))
dat$P <- factor(with(dat, ifelse(Treatment %in% c('P', 'NP'), 'yesP', 'noP')))

# perform PerMANOVA using Euclidean distances (for RDA)
adonis(dist(otu_table(phy), method='euclidean') ~ SampleType * N * P, 
       data=dat, strata=dat$BlockID)

An assumption of these analyses is that the dispersion (variance) is not different among groups. We can test this assumption with the betadisper function.

# test for 'SampleType', which has the most power.
anova(betadisper(dist(otu_table(phy), method='euclidean'), dat$SampleType))
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Response: Distances
##           Df   Sum Sq   Mean Sq F value  Pr(>F)  
## Groups     1 0.023171 0.0231709  2.9725 0.09704 .
## Residuals 25 0.194877 0.0077951                  
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

The test is not significant so we can assume that the assumption is not violated.

Canonical analysis - observational frameworks

By combining ordination techniques and multiple linear regression, we can use regression approaches to explain variation in one multivariate data table by variation in another multivariate data table from observations of the same objects. Prior to the availability of suitable software programs, principal components were extracted from the ordination of the explanatory matrix and then related to the ordination of the response matrix; this approach is named indirect gradient analysis. It has gradually been replaced by canonical analysis, or direct gradient analysis, in which the explanatory matrix is directly involved in the ordination of the response matrix.

When analysing the continuous variables, we need to decide whether it matters that they vary on the same scale or not. Variables that have a larger mean and, therefore, greater variance will contribute more to explaining variation in the data. This might be justified in some cases but in many cases comparing variables on the same absolute scale is not ecologically meaningful (e.g., concentrations of different nutrients that are required at different levels). In addition, the differences can come down to the the units in which the variable was measured (e.g., % versus ppm).

# standardise the data to 'mean=0' and 'sd=1' (or as close as possible) 
dat.con.std <- decostand(dat.con, method='standardize')

# check the results yourself
summary(dat.con.std)

Some functions allow for categorical variables in the model while others do not. To avoid problems, it is best to convert these to numeric variables, with each level within a category represented by a separate variable weighted by its frequency in the data. The code below shows you how to use functions in the ade4 library to do this conversion. Note that we don’t load the library since it includes the function ade4::cca, which we do not want to mask vegan::cca.

# for only categorical predictors
dat.hs <- ade4::dudi.hillsmith(dat.cat, scannf=F, nf=2)$tab

In the examples below, we will focus only on the standardised continuous variables, although we will include our treatments in plotting.

Choosing an approach

As for unconstrained ordination, there are several options and the choice of which to use depends on the characteristics of the data in the OTU matrix. Some of these approaches can be performed using phyloseq functions but they are no longer more convenient than the functions in vegan on which they are based. Therefore, we will use the vegan functions directly from here on out, with the occasional help from QsRutils functions.

# extract the OTU table
Y <- veganotu(phy)

# extract the sample data from the 'phyloseq' object
# then remove the 'SampleID' column
dat <- data.frame(sample_data(phy))
dat <- select(dat, -SampleID)

# select the continuous variables to use in the constraint (Y)
# then standardise
X <- select_if(dat, is.numeric)
X <- decostand(X, method='standardize')
  1. Redundancy analysis (RDA) – RDA is an extension of PCA and, as such, is appropriate for estimating the importance of constraining variables along short gradients that display low species turnover (recall Section~).
# RDA
res <- rda(Y ~ ., data=X)
plot(res, xlab=ord_labels(res)[1], ylab=ord_labels(res)[2])

  1. Canonical correspondence analysis (CCA) – CCA is an extension of CA, but serves the same purpose as RDA in relation to PCA. It may be preferred over RDA for long gradients, over which species distributions are limited to a subset of the gradient and do not overlap for many species (recall Section~), but dbRDA approaches can also be used (see below).
# CCA
res <- cca(Y ~ ., data=X)
plot(res, xlab=ord_labels(res)[1], ylab=ord_labels(res)[2])

  1. Distance-based RDA (dbRDA) or constrained analysis of principle coordinates (CAP) –
# dbRDA 
# note the result is the same as for RDA when using euclidean distances
res <- capscale(Y ~ ., data=X, distance='euclidean')
plot(res, xlab=ord_labels(res)[1], ylab=ord_labels(res)[2])

Despite the fact that we were able to explain XX% of the variation in the OTU matrix, the result was not statistically significant. This may be because we threw all of our explanatory variables at the analysis without considering whether they explained the variation efficiently. Simply including all of the data without providing any thought as to which data may be useful is unlikely to generate an interpretable response.

There are multiple approaches to select only the variables that are explaining variation efficiently.

  1. Variance inflation factors (VIF)
# calculate variance inflation

We can test the significance of each partition by performing RDA and conditioning the OTU matrix with all of the other partitions than the one that we are focussing on in that analysis. For example:

# Test the 'Treatment' partition (X3)
# first argument contains the community data 
# second argument is the partition of interest (constraint)
# third argument is a column-bound dataframe of remaining partitions (condition)
rda.x3 <- rda(Y, X3, cbind(X1, X2, X4))

# test significance
anova(rda.x3)
## Permutation test for rda under reduced model
